":"I have code that looks like this:\r\n```\r\ndef plot_heatmap(A, ax, title=\"3-block SBM (first two blocks indistinguishable)\", show_cbar=True):\r\n    cmap = matplotlib.colors.ListedColormap([\"white\", 'black'])\r\n    with sns.plotting_context(\"talk\", font_scale=1):\r\n        ax = heatmap(A, cmap=cmap, ax=ax)\r\n        ax.set_title(title)\r\n        cbar = ax.collections[0].colorbar\r\n        if show_cbar:\r\n            cbar.set_ticks([0.25, .75])\r\n            cbar.set_ticklabels(['No Edge', 'Edge'])\r\n            cbar.ax.set_frame_on(True)\r\n        else:\r\n            cbar.remove()\r\n            \r\n        \r\nplot_heatmap(A, ax)\r\n```\r\n\r\nUsing `sns.heatmap` (along with some additional arguments), this code produces a heatmap that looks like this:\r\n<img width=\"652\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2021-03-26 at 6 47 47 PM\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12386450/112700112-cd2b3700-8e63-11eb-8c36-3937159da9d2.png\">\r\n\r\nHowever, when I use `graspologic.plot.heatmap` (using effectively the same arguments, given the seaborn wrapper under the hood), the heatmap looks like this:\r\n<img width=\"661\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2021-03-26 at 6 48 39 PM\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12386450/112700186-ed5af600-8e63-11eb-8ab2-119b5e6c9170.png\">\r\n\r\nWhen I change `cmap = matplotlib.colors.ListedColormap([\"white\", 'black'])` to `cmap = matplotlib.colors.ListedColormap([\"white\", \"white\", \"black\"])`, the heatmap looks fine again. I think maybe the first argument to `ListedColormap` is being ignored? \r\n\r\nI'm gonna play around with this and hopefully make a bugfix PR. @bdpedigo any off-the-top-of-your-head ideas as to why this could be happening?","closed_by":{"login":"loftusa","id":12386450,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEyMzg2NDUw","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/12386450?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/loftusa","html_url":"https://github.com/loftusa","followers_url":"https://ap